from numpy import set_printoptions
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest
from sklearn.feature_selection import chi2

X = data.drop(columns=['Diabetes_binary'])
Y = data['Diabetes_binary']

# Use SelectKBest with the Chi-squared (chi2) test
test = SelectKBest(score_func=chi2, k='all')  # Set k='all' to get scores for all features
fit = test.fit(X, Y)  # Fit the data

# Set print options to limit precision to 2 decimal points
set_printoptions(precision=2)

# Get feature scores
feature_scores = fit.scores_

# Create a DataFrame to display feature names and their respective scores
feature_scores_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature': X.columns,
    'Score': feature_scores
})

# Sort features by score in descending order
feature_scores_df = feature_scores_df.sort_values(by='Score', ascending=False)

# Print the sorted feature scores
print(feature_scores_df)

from sklearn.feature_selection import RFE
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

# Define the Logistic Regression model
model = LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear')

# Define RFE with the model and set the number of features to select (e.g., 3 in this case)
rfe = RFE(model, n_features_to_select=3)

# Fit the RFE model
fit = rfe.fit(X, Y)

# Get the boolean mask of selected features (True means the feature is selected)
selected_features = fit.support_

# Get the ranking of the features (1 means selected)
ranking = fit.ranking_

# Create a DataFrame to display feature names, selection status, and ranking
rfe_results = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature': X.columns,
    'Selected': selected_features,
    'Ranking': ranking
})

# Sort by ranking to show the most important features first
rfe_results = rfe_results.sort_values(by='Ranking')

# Print the results
print(rfe_results)

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
# Define and apply PCA with 2 components
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
fit = pca.fit(X)

# Get the explained variance ratio
explained_variance_ratio = fit.explained_variance_ratio_

# Get the principal components
components = fit.components_

# Create a DataFrame to display the explained variance for each principal component
explained_variance_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Principal Component': ['PC1', 'PC2'],
    'Explained Variance Ratio': explained_variance_ratio
})

# Create a DataFrame to display the principal components and the feature loadings
components_df = pd.DataFrame(components, columns=X.columns, index=['PC1', 'PC2'])

# Print explained variance ratio
print("Explained Variance Ratio:")
print(explained_variance_df)

# Print principal component feature loadings
print("\nPrincipal Component Loadings:")
print(components_df)

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, classification_report

x = data[['BMI', 'HighBP', 'Age']]
y = data['Diabetes_binary']

x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x,y, test_size=0.2, random_state= 0)
model = LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear', random_state=0) # define model
model.fit(x_train, y_train)  # fit the model
y_pred = model.predict(x_test) # predict the model

score=model.score(x,y)
conf_m=confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred)
report = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)
#print('Model Accuracy:', score)
#print('Confusion Matrix:\n', conf_m)
print('report:', report)

# Predict probabilities (keep HighBP and Age constant)
fixed_highbp = 1
fixed_age = 50
probabilities = model.predict_proba(np.hstack([bmi_range, 
                                               np.full_like(bmi_range, fixed_highbp), 
                                               np.full_like(bmi_range, fixed_age)]))[:, 1]

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

x = data[['BMI', 'HighBP']]
y = data['Diabetes_binary']

SSE=[]
for k in range(1,20):
    knn=KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn.fit(x,y)
    pred_i=knn.predict(x)
    SSE.append(np.mean(pred_i != y))
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
plt.plot(range(1,20),SSE,color='b',linestyle='dashed',marker='o',markerfacecolor='r',markersize=10)
plt.show()
In[20]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

n_neighbors = 12

X = x.values
h = 0.2
clf = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=n_neighbors, weights='distance')
clf.fit(X, y)

# Create a mesh grid for the feature space
x_min, x_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1  # x-axis (BMI)
y_min, y_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1  # y-axis (HighBP)
xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, h), np.arange(y_min, y_max, h))  # grids

# Define color maps for predicted and actual values
cmap_l = ListedColormap(['#FFAAAA', '#AAFFAA', '#00AAFF'])  # Predicted
cmap_d = ListedColormap(['#FF0000', '#00FF00', '#AA00FF'])  # Actual

# Predict the values for the grid
Z = clf.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)

# Create the plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.pcolormesh(xx, yy, Z, cmap=cmap_l, shading='auto')  # Predicted values on background
plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y, cmap=cmap_d, edgecolor='k')  # Actual values
plt.xlim(xx.min(), xx.max())
plt.ylim(yy.min(), yy.max())
plt.title("KNN Classification (k=12)")
plt.show()

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

# Assuming 'data' is your DataFrame
x = data[['BMI', 'HighBP']]
y = data['Diabetes_binary']

# Split the dataset into training and testing sets
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Train the KNN model with k = 12
optimal_k = 12
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=optimal_k)
knn.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the test set
predictions = knn.predict(x_test)

# Calculate accuracy
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, predictions)
print(f'Accuracy of KNN: {accuracy*100:.2f}')

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB

X = x.values
y = y

# Step size for mesh grid
h = 0.2

# Create a mesh grid for the feature space
x_min, x_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1  # x-axis (BMI)
y_min, y_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1  # y-axis (HighBP)
xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, h), np.arange(y_min, y_max, h))  # grids

# Train the Naive Bayes model
gnb = GaussianNB()
gnb.fit(X, y)

# Predict the values for the grid
Z_nb = gnb.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
Z_nb = Z_nb.reshape(xx.shape)

# Define color maps for predicted and actual values
cmap_l = ListedColormap(['#FFAAAA', '#AAFFAA', '#00AAFF'])  # Predicted
cmap_d = ListedColormap(['#FF0000', '#00FF00', '#AA00FF'])  # Actual

# Create the plot for Naive Bayes
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.pcolormesh(xx, yy, Z_nb, cmap=cmap_l, shading='auto')  # Predicted values on background
plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y, cmap=cmap_d, edgecolor='k')  # Actual values
plt.xlim(xx.min(), xx.max())
plt.ylim(yy.min(), yy.max())
plt.title("Nave Bayes Classifier")
plt.show()

# define- fit - predict - find the accuracy of models
from sklearn import svm
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

# sigmoid kernel
svc=svm.SVC(kernel='sigmoid', C=1).fit(x,y)
svc_pred=svc.predict(x)
print('sigmoid accuracy',accuracy_score(y,svc_pred)*100)

# linear svm
lin_svc=svm.LinearSVC(C=1, max_iter=10000).fit(x,y)
lsvc_pred=lin_svc.predict(x)
print('linear svc accuracy',accuracy_score(y,lsvc_pred)*100)

# rbf kernel
rbf_svc=svm.SVC(kernel='rbf', gamma=0.7, C=1).fit(x,y)
rsvc_pred=rbf_svc.predict(x)
print('rbf accuracy',accuracy_score(y,rsvc_pred)*100)

# poly kernel, degree 3 ax^3+bx^2+cx+d
poly_svc=svm.SVC(kernel='poly', degree=3, C=1).fit(x,y)
psvc_pred=poly_svc.predict(x)
print('poly accuracy',accuracy_score(y,psvc_pred)*100)

h = 0.02
x_min, x_max = x.iloc[:,0].min()-1, x.iloc[:,0].max()+1 
y_min, y_max = x.iloc[:,1].min()-1, x.iloc[:,1].max()+1 
xx, yy=np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min,x_max,h),np.arange(y_min,y_max,h))

titles=['Sigmoid kernel','linear svc','rbf','poly']

for i, clf in enumerate((svc, lin_svc, rbf_svc, poly_svc)):
    # create 4 subplots
    plt.subplot(2,2,i+1)
    plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.4,hspace=0.4)
    
    # predict test results based on BMI and HighBP
    Z=clf.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(),yy.ravel()])
    Z=Z.reshape(xx.shape)
    
    # plot actual and predicted values
    plt.contourf(xx,yy,Z,cmap=plt.cm.coolwarm, alpha=0.8)
    plt.scatter(x.iloc[:,0],x.iloc[:,1], c=y, cmap=plt.cm.coolwarm)
    
    # modify the graphs by adding labels, titles, ...
    plt.xlabel('BMI, HighBP')
    plt.ylabel('Test results')
    plt.xlim(xx.min(),xx.max())
    plt.ylim(yy.min(),yy.max())
    plt.xticks(())
    plt.yticks(())
    plt.title(titles[i])
    
plt.show()
